INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2800','letter','1774-05-12','Boston','MA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','I AM extremely afflicted with the relation your father gave me of the return of your disorder. I fear you have taken some cold.','ltr_jod2800.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2802','letter','1774-06-29','New York','NY','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','I HAVE a great deal of leisure, which I chiefly employ in scribbling, that my mind may not stand still or run back, like my fortune.','ltr_jod2802.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2803','letter','1774-07-06','Falmouth','MA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','MOBS are the trite topic of declamation and invective among all the ministerial people far and near. They are grown universally learned in the nature, tendency and consequences of them, and very elegant and pathetic in descanting upon them.','ltr_jod2803.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2804','letter','1774-07-07','Falmouth','MA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','I am engaged in a famous cause. The cause of King of Scarborough versus a mob that broke into his house and rifled his papers and terrified him, his wife, children and servants in the night.','ltr_jod2804.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2805','letter','1774-07-09','Falmouth','MA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','I NEVER enjoyed better health in any of my journeys,but this has been the most tedious, the most irk some, the most gloomy and melancholy I ever made. I cannot, with all my philosophy and Christian resignation, keep up my spirits.','ltr_jod2805.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2806','letter','1774-08-28','Princeton','NJ','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','The education of our children is never out of my mind. Train them to virtue. Habituate them to industry, activity and spirit. Make them consider every vice as shameful and unmanly.','ltr_jod2806.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2807','letter','1774-09-08','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','We have received a confused account from Boston of a dreadful catastrophe. The particulars we have not heard. We are waiting with the utmost anxiety and impatience, for further intelligence.','ltr_jod2807.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2808','letter','1774-09-14','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','A Tory here is the most despicable animal in the creation. Spiders, toads, snakes are their only proper emblems.','ltr_jod2808.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2809','letter','1774-09-16','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','we were so divided in religious sentiments ; some Episcopalians, some Quakers, some Anabaptists, some Presbyterians, and some Congregationalists, that we could not join in the same act of worship.','ltr_jod2809.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2810','letter','1774-09-18','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','The proceedings of the Congress are all a profound secret as yet, except two votes which were passed yesterday, and ordered to be printed. You will see them from every quarter.','ltr_jod2810.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2811','letter','1774-09-18','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','When the horrid news was brought here of the bombardment of Boston, which made us completely miserable for two days, we saw proofs both of the sympathy and the resolution of the continent. War! war! war! was the cry','ltr_jod2811.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2812','letter','1774-09-20','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','I am anxious to know how you can live without government But the experiment must be tried. The evils will not be found so dreadful as you apprehend them.','ltr_jod2812.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2813','letter','1774-09-23','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','Fifty gentlemen meeting together, all strangers, are not acquainted with each other\'s language, ideas, views, designs.','ltr_jod2813.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2814','letter','1774-09-29','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','Patience, forbearance, long suffering are the lessons taught here for our province, and at the same time, absolute and open resistance to the new Government.','ltr_jod2814.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2815','letter','1774-10-07','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','I wish I could write to you a dozen letters every day. But the business before me is so arduous, and takes up my time so entirely, that I cannot write often.','ltr_jod2815.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2816','letter','1774-10-09','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','This assembly is like no other that ever existed. Every man in it is a great roan, an orator, a critic, a statesman ; and therefore, every man upon every question, must show his oratory, his criticism, and his political abilities.','ltr_jod2816.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2817','letter','1775-04-30','Hartford','CT','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','The people of the city have seized the city arms and ammunition out of the hands of the Mayor, who is a creature of the Governor. Lord North will certainly be disappointed in his expectation of seducing New York.','ltr_jod2817.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2818','letter','1775-05-02','Hartford','CT','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','OUR hearts arc bleeding for the poor people of Boston. What will or can be done for them, I can\'t conceive. God preserve them.','ltr_jod2818.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2819','letter','1775-05-02','Hartford','CT','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','It is arrogance and presumption, in human sagacity, to pretend to penetrate far into the designs of Heaven.','ltr_jod2819.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2820','letter','1775-06-10','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','I wish I could write freely to you, my dear, but I cannot. The scene before me is complicated enough. It requires better eyes, and better nerves than mine ; yet I will not despond.','ltr_jod2820.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2821','letter','1775-06-10','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','DR. CHURCH has given me a lotion which has helped my eyes so much that I hope you will hear from me oftener than you have done.','ltr_jod2821.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2822','letter','1775-06-11','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','I can now inform you, that the Congress have made choice of the modest and virtuous, the amiable, generous and brave George Washington, Esquire, to be General of the American army','ltr_jod2822.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2823','letter','1775-06-18','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','THIS letter, I presume, will go by the brave and amiable General Washington. Our army will have a group of officers equal to any service.','ltr_jod2823.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2824','letter','1775-06-23','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','I HAVE this morning been out of town, to accompany our Generals, Washington, Lee and Schuyler, a little way on their journey to the American camp, before Boston.','ltr_jod2824.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2825','letter','1775-07-07','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','It is not at all surprising to me, that the wanton, cruel, and infamous conflagration of Charlestown, the place of your father\'s nativity, should afllict him. Let him know that I sincerely condole with him on that melancholy event.','ltr_jod2825.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2826','letter','1775-07-23','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','Dr. Franklin has Been very constant in his attendance on Congress from the beginning. His conduct has been composed and grave, and, in the opinion of many gentlemen, very reserved.','ltr_jod2826.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2827','letter','1775-07-30','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','We have nothing new, but the arrival of some powder. Three little vessels have certainly arrived, making about ten tons in the whole, and four or five tons have arrived from South Carolina.','ltr_jod2827.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2828','letter','1775-10-01','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','I feel, I tremble for you. Poor Tommy ! I hope, by this time, however, he has recovered his plump cheeks, and his fine tyloom.','ltr_jod2828.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2829','letter','1775-10-02','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','I must beg to be excused, my dear, from hinting at anything for the future, of public persons or things. Secrecy is so much exacted. But thus much I may say, that I never saw so serious and determined a spirit.','ltr_jod2829.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2830','letter','1775-10-07','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','The situation of things is so alarming, that it is our duty to prepare our minds and hearts for every event even the worst From my earliest entrance into life, I have been engaged in the public cause of America','ltr_jod2830.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2831','letter','1775-10-10','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','Pray, bundle up every paper, not already hid, and conceal them in impenetrable darkness. Nobody knows what may occur.','ltr_jod2831.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2832','letter','1775-10-13','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','It is the constitution under which we are born, that if we live long ourselves, we must bury our parents, and all our elder relations, and many of those who are younger.','ltr_jod2832.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2833','letter','1775-10-19','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','Really it is very painful to be four hundred miles from one\'s family and friends, when we know they are in affliction. It seems as if it would be a joy to me to fly home, even to share with you your burdens and misfortunes.','ltr_jod2833.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2834','letter','1775-10-23','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','If I could write as well as you, my sorrow would be as eloquent as yours, but, upon my word, I cannot.','ltr_jod2834.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2835','letter','1775-10-29','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','Does not natural morality and much more Christian benevolence make it our indispensable duty to lay ourselves out to serve our fellow Creatures, to the utmost, of our power, in promoting and supporting those great political systems and general regulations, upon which the happiness of multitudes depends?','ltr_jod2835.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2836','letter','1775-10-29','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','Education makes a greater difference between man and man, than nature has made between man and brute. The virtues and powers to which men may be trained, by early education and constant discipline, are truly sublime and astonishing.','ltr_jod2836.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2837','letter','1775-10-29','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','New England has, in many respects, the advantage of every other colony in America, and, indeed, of every other part of the world that I know any thing of.','ltr_jod2837.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2838','letter','1775-11-04','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','This town is as secure from the cannon and men of war as the moon is. I wish she had a little of your fortitude. I had rather be killed by a ball than live in such continual fears as she does.','ltr_jod2838.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2839','letter','1775-12-03','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','although I have a number of friends and many relations, who are very dear to me, yet all the friendship I have for others is far unequal to that which warms my heart for you.','ltr_jod2839.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2840','letter','1776-01-24','Watertown','NY','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','I dined at Colonel Mifllin\'s with the General and lady, and a vast collection of other company, among whom were six or seven sachems and warriors of the French Caghnawaga Indians with several of their wives and children.','ltr_jod2840.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2841','letter','1776-02-11','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','There is a deep anxiety, a kind of thoughtful melancholy, and in some, a lowness of spirits approaching to despondency, prevailing through the southern colonies, at present, very similar to what I have often observed in Boston','ltr_jod2841.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2842','letter','1776-02-00','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','LEE is at York, and we have requested a battalion of Philadelphia associators, together with a regiment of Jersey minute men, to march to his assistance.','ltr_jod2842.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2843','letter','1776-02-18','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','I SENT you from New York a pamphlet intitled \"Common Sense,\" written in vindication of doctrines, which there is reason to expect, that the further encroachments of tyranny and depredations of oppression will soon make the common faith','ltr_jod2843.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2844','letter','1776-03-17','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','Your vicinity to such scenes of carnage and desolation as, I fear, are now to be seen in Boston and its environs, will throw you into much distress, but I believe in my conscience, I feel more here than you do.','ltr_jod2844.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2845','letter','1776-03-19','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','I am much pleased with your caution in your letter, in avoiding names both of persons and places, or any other circumstances, which might designate to strangers the writer, or the person written to, or the persons mentioned.','ltr_jod2845.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2846','letter','1776-03-29','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','I GIVE you joy of Boston and Charlestown, once more the habitation of Americans. ','ltr_jod2846.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2847','letter','1776-04-12','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','You will see by the papers the news, the speculations, and the political plans of the day. The ports are opened wide enough at last, and privateers are allowed to prey upon British trade.','ltr_jod2847.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2848','letter','1776-04-14','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','You ask where the fleet is? The enclosed papers will inform you. You ask, what sort of defence Virginia can make? I believe they will make an able defence.','ltr_jod2848.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2849','letter','1776-04-15','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','I SEND you every newspaper that comes out, and I send you, now and then, a few sheets of paper, but this article is as scarce here, as with you. I would send a quire, if I could get a conveyance.','ltr_jod2849.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2850','letter','1776-04-23','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','This curious character of a barber, I have a great inclination to draw, for your amusement. He is a little dapper fellow, short and small, but active and lively. A tongue as fluent and voluble as you please','ltr_jod2850.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2851','letter','1775-05-29','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','The Congress will support the Massachusetts. There is a good spirit here. But we have an amazing field of business before us. When I shall have the joy of meeting you and our little ones, I know not.','ltr_jod2851.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2852','letter','1776-04-28','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','Instead of domestic felicity, I am destined to public contentions. Instead of rural felicity, I must reconcile myself to the smoke and noise of a city. In the place of private peace, I must be distracted with the vexation of developing the deep intrigues of politicians','ltr_jod2852.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2853','letter','1776-05-12','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','What shall I do with my office ? I want to resign it for a thousand reasons. Would you advise me ?','ltr_jod2853.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2854','letter','1776-05-17','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','I HAVE this morning heard Mr. Duffield, upon the signs of the times. He ran a parallel between the case of Israel, and that of America ; and between the conduct of Pharaoh, and that of George.','ltr_jod2854.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2855','letter','1776-05-22','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','Generals Gates and Mifflin are now here: General Washington will be here to-morrow, when we shall consult and deliberate concerning the operations of the ensuing campaign.','ltr_jod2855.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2856','letter','1776-05-27','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','I think you shine as a stateswoman of late, as well as a farmeress. Pray where do you get your maxims of state ? They are very apropos.','ltr_jod2856.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2857','letter','1776-06-02','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','YESTERDAY I dined with Captain Richards, the gentle man who made me the present of the brass pistols. We had cherries, strawberries and green peas in plenty.','ltr_jod2857.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2858','letter','1776-06-16','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','I wish our uncle had as much ambition, as he has virtue and ability. A deficiency of ambition is as criminal and injurious as an excess of it. Tell him I say so.','ltr_jod2858.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2859','letter','1776-06-26','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','Our misfortunes in Canada are enough to melt a heart of stone. The small pox is ten times more terrible than Britons, Canadians and Indians, together. This was the cause of our precipitate retreat from Quebec.','ltr_jod2859.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2860','letter','1776-07-03','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','I was informed, a day or two before the receipt of your letter, that you was gone to Plymouth, by Mrs. Polly Palmer, who was obliging enough, in your absence, to send me the particulars of the expedition to the lower harbor against the men of war.','ltr_jod2860.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2861','letter','1776-07-03','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','HAD a Declaration of Independency been made seven months ago, it would have been attended with many great and glorious effects. We might, before this hour, have formed alliances with foreign states.','ltr_jod2861.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2862','letter','1776-07-07','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','The design of our enemy now seems to be, a powerful invasion of New York and New Jersey. The Halifax fleet and army is arrived, and another fleet and army under Lord Howe is expected to join them.','ltr_jod2862.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2863','letter','1776-07-07','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','Letters, like conversation, should be free, easy, and familiar. Simplicity and familiarity are the characteristics of this kind of writing. Affectation is as disagreeable in a letter, as in conversation','ltr_jod2863.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2864','letter','1776-07-10','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','You will sec, by the newspapers, which I, from time to time, enclose, with what rapidity the colonies proceed in their political manoeuvres. How many calamities might have been avoided, if these measures had been taken twelve months ago','ltr_jod2864.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2865','letter','1776-07-11','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','The militia of Maryland, New Jersey, Pennsylvania and the lower counties are marching with much alacrity, and a laudable zeal to take care of Howe and his army at Staten Island.','ltr_jod2865.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2866','letter','1776-07-15','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','There is a most amiable, laudable and gallant spirit prevailing in these middle colonies. The militia turn out in great numbers, and in high spirits, in New Jersey, Pennsylvania, Maryland and Delaware, so that we hope to resist Howe and his myrmidons.','ltr_jod2866.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2867','letter','1776-07-20','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','We had yesterday an express from General Lee in Charleston, South Carolina, with an account of a brilliant little action between the armament under Clinton and Cornwallis, and a battery on Sullivan\'s Island','ltr_jod2867.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2868','letter','1776-07-20','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','If you were too busy to write, I hoped that some kind hand would have been found to let me know something about you. Do my friends think that I have been a politician so long, as to have lost all feeling?','ltr_jod2868.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2869','letter','1776-07-29','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','How are you all this morning ? Sick, weak, faint, in pain, or pretty well recovered ? By this time, you are well acquainted with the small pox. Pray, how do you like it ?','ltr_jod2869.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2870','letter','1776-08-03','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','Went this morning to the Baptist meeting, in hopes of hearing Mr. Stillman, but was disappointed. He was there, but another gentleman preached.','ltr_jod2870.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2871','letter','1776-08-12','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','A French vessel, a pretty large brigantine, deeply laden, arrived here yesterday, from Martinique. She had fifty barrels of limes, which are all sold, already, at such prices, that the amount of them will be sufficient to load the brig with flour.','ltr_jod2871.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2872','letter','1776-08-12','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','I want to be informed of the state of things with you ; whether there is a scarcity of provisions of any kind, of West India articles, of clothing ? Whether any trade is carried on, any fishery ?','ltr_jod2872.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2873','letter','1776-08-14','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','THIS is the anniversary of a memorable day in the history of America. A day when the principle of American resistance and independence was first asserted and carried into action. The stamp office fell before the rising spirit of our countrymen.','ltr_jod2873.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2874','letter','1776-08-18','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','I have seen in this world but a little of that pure flame of patriotism which certainly burns in some breasts. There is much of the ostentation and affectation of it. I have known a few, who could not bear to entertain a selfish design','ltr_jod2874.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2875','letter','1776-08-21','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','YESTERDAY morning, I took a walk into Arch street to see Mr. Peale\'s Painter\'s room. Peale is from Maryland, a tender, soft, affectionate creature.','ltr_jod2875.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2876','letter','1776-08-25','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','Another winter, will do much for us too. We shall have more and better soldiers. We shall be better armed. We shall have a greater force at sea. We shall have more trade. Our artillery will be greatly increased, our officers will have more experience, and our soldiers more discipline, our politicians more courage and confidence, and our enemies less hope.','ltr_jod2876.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2877','letter','1776-09-05','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','But it is uncertain when I shall set off for home. I will not go at present Affairs are too delicate and critical. The panic may seize I whom it will. It shall not seize me. I will stay here until the public countenance is better, or much worse.','ltr_jod2877.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2878','letter','1776-09-06','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','THIS day, I think, has been the most remarkable of all. Sullivan came here from Lord Howe, five days ago,with a message, that his lordship desired a half an hour\'s conversation with some of the members of Congress in their private capacities.','ltr_jod2878.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2879','letter','1776-09-14','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','YESTERDAY morning, I returned with Dr. Franklin and Mr. Rutledge from Staten Island, where we met Lord Howe, and had about three hours conversation with him.','ltr_jod2879.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2880','letter','1776-09-22','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','WE have at last agreed upon a plan for forming a regular army. We have offered twenty dollars and a hundred acres of land to every man who will enlist during the war.','ltr_jod2880.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2881','letter','1776-10-01','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','I will not say, that I expect to run distracted, to grow melancholy, to drop in an apoplexy or fall into a consumption ; but I do say, it is little less than a miracle, that one or other of these misfortunes has not befallen me before now.','ltr_jod2881.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2882','letter','1776-10-04','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','I AM seated in a large library room with eight gentlemen round about me, all engaged in conversation. Amidst these interruptions, how shall I make it out to write a letter ?','ltr_jod2882.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2883','letter','1776-10-08','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','I assure you, we are as much at a loss, about affairs at New York, as you are. In general, our Generals were outgeneraled on Long Island, and Sullivan and Stirling with a thousand men were made prisoners','ltr_jod2883.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2884','letter','1776-10-11','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','But I am coming to make my apology in person. I yesterday, asked and obtained leave of absence.','ltr_jod2884.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2885','letter','1777-01-09','Dedham','MA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','Present my affection in the tenderest manner to my little deserving daughter and my amiable sons. It was cruel parting this morning. My heart was most deeply affected although I had the presence of mind to appear composed.','ltr_jod2885.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2886','letter','1777-01-13','Hartford','CT','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','Our spirits have been cheered by two or three pieces of good news, which Commissary Trumbull, who is now with me, tells us he saw yesterday, in a letter from General Washington, who has gained another considerable advantage of the enemy at Stony Brook','ltr_jod2886.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2887','letter','1777-01-14','Hartford','CT','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','IT is now generally believed that General Washington has killed and taken at least two thousand of Mr. Howe\'s army since Christmas. Indeed the evidence of it is from the General\'s own letters.','ltr_jod2887.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2888','letter','1777-00-00','Fishkill','NY','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','AFTER a march like that of Hannibal over the Alps, we arrived, last night, at this place, where we found the utmost difficulty to get forage for our horses, and lodgings for ourselves','ltr_jod2888.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2889','letter','1777-01-19','Poughkeepsie','NY','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','This, as well as Fishkill, is a pretty village. We are almost wholly among the Dutch. Zealous against the Tories, who have not half the tranquillity here, that they have in the town of Boston','ltr_jod2889.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2890','letter','1777-01-20','Bethlehem','NY','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','General Washington, with his little army, is at Morristown. Cornwallis, with his larger one, at Brunswick. Oh ! that the continental army was full. Now is the time!','ltr_jod2890.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2891','letter','1777-01-24','Eaton','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','WE have at last crossed the Delaware and are agree ably lodged at Easton, a little town situated on a point of land formed by the Delaware on one side, and the river Lehigh on the other.','ltr_jod2891.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2892','letter','1777-02-02','Baltimore','MD','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','Baltimore is a very pretty town, situated on Patapsco river, which empties itself into the great bay of Chesapeake. The inhabitants are all good Whigs, having some time ago banished all the Tories from among them.','ltr_jod2892.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2893','letter','1777-02-03','Baltimore','MD','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','I shall take opportunities to describe this town and State more particularly to you hereafter. I shall inquire into their religion, their laws, their customs, their manners, their descent and education, their learning, their schools and colleges, and their morals.','ltr_jod2893.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2894','letter','1777-02-07','Baltimore','MD','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','I AM at last, after a great deal of difficulty, settled in comfortable quarters, but at an infinite expense.','ltr_jod2894.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2895','letter','1777-02-07','Baltimore','MD','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','I THINK, in some letter I sent you since I left Bethlehem, I promised you a more particular account of that curious and remarkable town.','ltr_jod2895.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2896','letter','1777-02-10','Baltimore','MD','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','FELL\'s point, which I mentioned in a letter this morn ing, has a considerable number of houses upon it. The shipping all lies now at this point.','ltr_jod2896.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2897','letter','1777-02-15','Baltimore','MD','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','We have from New Hampshire a Colonel Thornton, a physician by profession, a man of humor. He has a large budget of droll stories with which he entertains company perpetually.','ltr_jod2897.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2898','letter','1777-02-17','Baltimore','MD','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','Howe, as you know my opinion always was, will repent his mad march through the Jerseys. The people of that Commonwealth begin to raise their spirits exceedingly and to be firmer than ever.','ltr_jod2898.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2899','letter','1777-02-21','Baltimore','MD','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','Many persons are extremely dissatisfied with numbers of the generaf officers of the highest rank. I Don\'t mean the Commander-in-chief, his character is justly very high','ltr_jod2899.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2900','letter','1777-03-07','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','This city is a dull place, in comparison of what it was. More than one half of the inhabitants have removed into the country, as it was their wisdom to do.','ltr_jod2900.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2901','letter','1777-03-16','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','What pleasure has not this vile war deprived me of? I want to wander in my meadows, to ramble over my mountains, and to sit, in solitude, or with her who has all my heart, by the side of the brooks.','ltr_jod2901.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2902','letter','1777-03-23','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','\" A PLOT, a plot ! a horrid plot ! Mr. A.,\" says my barber, this morning.','ltr_jod2902.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2903','letter','1777-03-31','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','Accidents have thrown so many letters into the hands of the enemy, and they take such a malicious pleasure in exposing them, that I choose they should have nothing but trifles from me to expose.','ltr_jod2903.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2904','letter','1777-04-02','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','You think I dont t write politics enough. Indeed I have a surfeit of them. But I shall give you now and then a taste, since you have such a gout for them.','ltr_jod2904.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2905','letter','1777-04-03','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','As you seem so inquisitive about politics, I will indulge you so far (indulge. I say. Observe that word, indulge ! I suppose you will say, it ought to have been, oblige,)','ltr_jod2905.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2906','letter','1777-04-06','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','You have had many rumors propagated among you which I suppose you know not how to account for. One was, that Congress, the last summer, had tied the hands of General Washington, and would not let him fight, particularly on the White plains.','ltr_jod2906.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2907','letter','1777-04-08','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','Lee fares as well as a man in close prison can fare, I suppose, constantly guarded and watched. I fancy Howe will engage that he shall be treated as a prisoner of war, and in that case we shall all be easy.','ltr_jod2907.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2908','letter','1777-04-13','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','ENCLOSED with this, you have a correspondence between the two Generals concerning the cartel for the exchange of prisoners. Washington is in the right, and has maintained his argument with a delicacy and dignity, which do him much honor','ltr_jod2908.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2909','letter','1777-04-13','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','The graves of the soldiers, who have been buried in this ground from the hospital and bettering house during the course of the last summer, fall and winter, dead of the smallpox and camp diseases, are enough to make the heart of stone to melt away.','ltr_jod2909.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2910','letter','1777-04-19','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','WE have now an ample representation from New York. It consists of six delegates, and they are to all appearance as high, as decisive, and as determined as any men ever were or can be.','ltr_jod2910.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2911','letter','1777-04-23','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','MY barber just left the chamber. The following curious dialogue was the amusement during the gay moments of shaving.','ltr_jod2911.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2912','letter','1777-04-26','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','Posterity! you will never know how much it cost the present generation to preserve your freedom! I hope you will make a good use of it If you do not, I shall repent in Heaven that I ever took half the pains to preserve it.','ltr_jod2912.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2913','letter','1777-04-27','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','My barber, whom I quote as often as ever I did any authority, says, \"he has read histories of cruelty and he has read romances of cruelty, but the cruelty of the British exceeds all that he ever read.\"','ltr_jod2913.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2194','letter','1777-04-23','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','THERE is a clock calm at this time in the political and military hemispheres. The surface is smooth and the air serene. Not a breath nor a wave, no news nor noise.','ltr_jod2914.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2915','letter','1777-05-04','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','ENCLOSED with this you will have an Evening Post containing some of the tender mercies of the barbarians to their prisoners.','ltr_jod2915.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2916','letter','1777-05-07','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','Some merchant ships are arrived this week from Mary land. They were first chased by men of war in attempting to get into Chesapeake Bay.','ltr_jod2916.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2917','letter','1777-05-10','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','THE day before yesterday, I took a walk with my friend Whipple to Mrs. Wells\'s, the sister of the famous Mrs. Wright, to see her wax-work.','ltr_jod2917.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2918','letter','1777-05-15','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','In the midst of infinite noise, hurry and bustle, I lead & lonely, melancholy life, mourning the loss of all the charms of life, which are my family, and all the amusements that I ever had in life, which is my farm.','ltr_jod2918.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2919','letter','1777-05-17','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','O ! that I could wander upon Perm\'s hill and in the meadows and mountains in its neighborhood, free from care ! But this is a felicity too great for me.','ltr_jod2919.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2920','letter','1777-05-22','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','I would give three guineas for a barrel of your cider. Not one drop is to be had here for gold, and wine is not to be had under six or eight dollars a gallon, and that very bad.','ltr_jod2920.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2921','letter','1777-05-25','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','I am ashamed of our farmers. They are a lazy, ignorant set ; in husbandry, I mean ; for they know infinitely more of every thing else than these.','ltr_jod2921.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2922','letter','1777-06-02','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','Revenge in ancient days, (you will see it through the whole Roman History) was esteemed a generous and an heroic passion. Nothing was too good for a friend, or too bad for an enemy.','ltr_jod2922.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2923','letter','1777-06-04','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','You will see, by the enclosed papers in a letter from my friend Parsons, a very handsome narration of one of the prettiest exploits of this war, a fine retaliation of the Danbury mischief.','ltr_jod2923.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2124','letter','1777-07-08','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','Next month completes three years that I have been devoted to the service of liberty. A slavery it has been to me, whatever the world may think of it.','ltr_jod2924.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2925','letter','1777-07-11','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','We have had no news from camp for three or four days. Mr. Howe, by the last advices, was manoeuvring his fleet arid army in such a manner as give us expectations of an expedition','ltr_jod2925.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2926','letter','1777-07-13','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','WE have a confused account from the northward of something unlucky at Ticonderoga, but cannot certainly tell what it is. I am much afraid we shall lose that post, as we did forts Washington and Lee','ltr_jod2926.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2927','letter','1777-08-11','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','An express from Sinnepuxent, a place between the Capes of Delaware and the Capes of Chesapeake, informs, that a fleet of one hundred sail was seen off that place last Thursday.','ltr_jod2927.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2928','letter','1777-08-11','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','THINK I have sometimes observed to you in conversation, that upon examining the biography of illustrious men, you will generally find some female about them, in the relation of mother, or wife, or sister, to whose instigation a great part of their merit is to be ascribed.','ltr_jod2928.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2929','letter','1777-08-19','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','I am sorry that you and the people of Boston were put to so much trouble, but glad to hear that such numbers determined to fly. The prices for carting which were demanded were detestable.','ltr_jod2929.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2930','letter','1777-08-19','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','Howe\'s fleet and army is still incognito. The gentlemen from South Carolina begin to tremble for Charleston. If Howe is under a judicial blindness, he may be gone there.','ltr_jod2930.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2931','letter','1777-08-20','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','I feel an inclination sometimes to write the history of the last three years, in imitation of Thucydides. There is a striking resemblance in several particulars between the Peloponnesian and the American war.','ltr_jod2931.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2932','letter','1777-08-21','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','They had been seen from the eastern shore of Virginia, standing off and on, for two days before. This method of coasting along the shore, and standing off and on, is very curious.','ltr_jod2932.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2933','letter','1777-08-23','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','IT is now no longer a secret where Mr. Howe\'s fleet is. We have authentic intelligence that it is arrived at the head of Chesapeake bay, above the river Patapsco, upon which the town of Baltimore stands.','ltr_jod2933.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2134','letter','1777-08-23','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','I think there is a reasonable ground for confidence, with the favor of Heaven, that Howe will not be able to reach this city.','ltr_jod2934.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2935','letter','1777-08-24','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','The lightning struck in several places. It struck the Quaker alms-house in Walnut street, between Third and Fourth streets, not far from Captain Duncan\'s, where I lodge.','ltr_jod2935.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2936','letter','1777-08-25','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','A letter from Chesapeake bay, dated yesterday morning, informs that the enemy had not then landed. ','ltr_jod2936.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2937','letter','1777-08-26','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','HOWE\'s army, at least about five thousand of them, besides his light horse, are landed upon the banks of the Elk river, and the disposition he has made of his forces indicates a design to rest and refresh both men and horses.','ltr_jod2937.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2938','letter','1777-08-29','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','General Washington, with a very numerous army, is between Wilmington and the Head of Elk. Howe will make but a pitiful figure.','ltr_jod2938.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2939','letter','1777-08-30','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','The enemy are in possession of the Head of Elk, a little town at the head of the river Elk, in which they found a quantity of corn and oats belonging to the States.','ltr_jod2939.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2940','letter','1777-09-01','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','A letter from General Washington, dated Saturday, informs that our light parties have brought in four-and- twenty prisoners more. So that the prisoners and deserters since Mr. Howe landed are near a hundred.','ltr_jod2940.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2941','letter','1777-09-02','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','Abigail','Adams','','There is but one course for us to take, and that is to renounce the use of all foreign commodities. For my own part, I never lived in my whole life so meanly and poorly as I do now, and yet my constituents will growl at my extravagance.','ltr_jod2941.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jod2942','letter','1775-07-25','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Adams','','James','Warren','','A certain great fortune and piddling genius, whose fame has been trumpeted so loudly, has given a silly cast to our whole doings.','ltr_jod2942.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters of John Adams, Addressed to His Wife. Edited by His Grandson, Charles Francis Adams, Volume I, 1841');
